question:
You're designing a distributed e-commerce system using a microservices architecture. The system must handle complex business transactions spanning multiple services (inventory, payment, shipping, notification). After several production incidents where partial transactions left the system in an inconsistent state, you decide to implement the Saga pattern.

Your initial implementation uses an orchestration-based approach:

@Service
public class OrderSagaOrchestrator {
    private final OrderService orderService;
    private final PaymentService paymentService;
    private final InventoryService inventoryService;
    private final ShippingService shippingService;
    private final NotificationService notificationService;

    @Transactional
    public OrderResult processOrder(Order order) {
        try {
            // Create order
            OrderDTO orderDTO = orderService.createOrder(order);

            // Reserve inventory
            InventoryResult inventoryResult = inventoryService.reserveItems(orderDTO.getItems());
            if (!inventoryResult.isSuccessful()) {
                orderService.updateOrderStatus(orderDTO.getId(), OrderStatus.FAILED);
                return OrderResult.failure("Inventory reservation failed");
            }

            // Process payment
            PaymentResult paymentResult = paymentService.processPayment(orderDTO.getPaymentDetails());
            if (!paymentResult.isSuccessful()) {
				// Compensating transaction			
                inventoryService.releaseItems(orderDTO.getItems());
                orderService.updateOrderStatus(orderDTO.getId(), OrderStatus.FAILED);
                return OrderResult.failure("Payment processing failed");
            }

            // Create shipment
            ShippingResult shippingResult = shippingService.createShipment(orderDTO);
            if (!shippingResult.isSuccessful()) {
                // Compensating transaction
                paymentService.refundPayment(paymentResult.getTransactionId());  
				// Compensating transaction
                inventoryService.releaseItems(orderDTO.getItems());  
                orderService.updateOrderStatus(orderDTO.getId(), OrderStatus.FAILED);
                return OrderResult.failure("Shipment creation failed");
            }

            // Send notification
            notificationService.sendOrderConfirmation(orderDTO);
            orderService.updateOrderStatus(orderDTO.getId(), OrderStatus.COMPLETED);
            return OrderResult.success(orderDTO.getId());

        } catch (Exception e) {
            // Handle exceptions...
            orderService.updateOrderStatus(order.getId(), OrderStatus.FAILED);
            return OrderResult.failure("Unexpected error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

After running load tests, you discover several architectural issues with this implementation.
What is the most significant architectural problem with this implementation?
